'''Reductive stress''' is the counterpart to [[oxidative stress]], where electron acceptors are expected to be mostly reduced. It can be caused by excess amounts of [[glutathione]], and can contribute to [[cytotoxicity]].<ref name="MyUser_Ncbi.nlm.nih.gov_January_28_2016c">{{cite journal |title= Glutathione-dependent reductive stress triggers mitochondrial oxidation and cytotoxicity|date= |author= |pmid=22202674 |doi=10.1096/fj.11-199869 |volume=26 |pmc=3316899 |year=2012 |journal=FASEB J. |pages=1442–51 | last1 = Zhang | first1 = H | last2 = Limphong | first2 = P | last3 = Pieper | first3 = J | last4 = Liu | first4 = Q | last5 = Rodesch | first5 = CK | last6 = Christians | first6 = E | last7 = Benjamin | first7 = IJ}}</ref><ref name="MyUser_Sciencedirect.com_January_28_2016c">{{cite journal |url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0005272815000377 |title=Increased reactive oxygen species production during reductive stress: The roles of mitochondrial glutathione and thioredoxin reductases |date= |author= |accessdate= January 28, 2016 |doi=10.1016/j.bbabio.2015.02.012 |volume=1847 |journal=Biochimica et Biophysica Acta (BBA) - Bioenergetics |pages=514–525}}</ref>
